        "<p>Gatsby took an arm of each of us and moved forward into the</p>\n<p>restaurant, whereupon Mr. Wolfshiem swallowed a new sentence he was</p>\n<p>starting and lapsed into a somnambulatory abstraction.</p>\n<p>â€œHighballs?â€ asked the head waiter.</p>\n<p>â€œThis is a nice restaurant here,â€ said Mr. Wolfshiem, looking at the</p>\n<p>presbyterian nymphs on the ceiling. â€œBut I like across the street</p>\n<p>better!â€</p>",
        "<p>â€œYes, highballs,â€ agreed Gatsby, and then to Mr. Wolfshiem: â€œItâ€™s too</p>\n<p>hot over there.â€</p>\n<p>â€œHot and smallâ€”yes,â€ said Mr. Wolfshiem, â€œbut full of memories.â€</p>\n<p>â€œWhat place is that?â€ I asked.</p>\n<p>â€œThe old Metropole.â€</p>\n<p>â€œThe old Metropole,â€ brooded Mr. Wolfshiem gloomily. â€œFilled with</p>\n<p>faces dead and gone. Filled with friends gone now forever. I canâ€™t</p>",
        "<p>forget so long as I live the night they shot Rosy Rosenthal there. It</p>\n<p>was six of us at the table, and Rosy had eat and drunk a lot all</p>\n<p>evening. When it was almost morning the waiter came up to him with a</p>\n<p>funny look and says somebody wants to speak to him outside. â€˜All</p>\n<p>right,â€™ says Rosy, and begins to get up, and I pulled him down in his</p>\n<p>chair.</p>\n<p>â€œâ€Šâ€˜Let the bastards come in here if they want you, Rosy, but donâ€™t</p>",
        "<p>you, so help me, move outside this room.â€™</p>\n<p>â€œIt was four oâ€™clock in the morning then, and if weâ€™d of raised the</p>\n<p>blinds weâ€™d of seen daylight.â€</p>\n<p>â€œDid he go?â€ I asked innocently.</p>\n<p>â€œSure he went.â€ Mr. Wolfshiemâ€™s nose flashed at me indignantly. â€œHe</p>\n<p>turned around in the door and says: â€˜Donâ€™t let that waiter take away</p>\n<p>my coffee!â€™ Then he went out on the sidewalk, and they shot him three</p>",
        "<p>times in his full belly and drove away.â€</p>\n<p>â€œFour of them were electrocuted,â€ I said, remembering.</p>\n<p>â€œFive, with Becker.â€ His nostrils turned to me in an interested way.</p>\n<p>â€œI understand youâ€™re looking for a business gonnegtion.â€</p>\n<p>The juxtaposition of these two remarks was startling. Gatsby answered</p>\n<p>for me:</p>\n<p>â€œOh, no,â€ he exclaimed, â€œthis isnâ€™t the man.â€</p>",
        "<p>â€œNo?â€ Mr. Wolfshiem seemed disappointed.</p>\n<p>â€œThis is just a friend. I told you weâ€™d talk about that some other</p>\n<p>time.â€</p>\n<p>â€œI beg your pardon,â€ said Mr. Wolfshiem, â€œI had a wrong man.â€</p>\n<p>A succulent hash arrived, and Mr. Wolfshiem, forgetting the more</p>\n<p>sentimental atmosphere of the old Metropole, began to eat with</p>\n<p>ferocious delicacy. His eyes, meanwhile, roved very slowly all around</p>",
        "<p>the roomâ€”he completed the arc by turning to inspect the people</p>\n<p>directly behind. I think that, except for my presence, he would have</p>\n<p>taken one short glance beneath our own table.</p>\n<p>â€œLook here, old sport,â€ said Gatsby, leaning toward me, â€œIâ€™m afraid I</p>\n<p>made you a little angry this morning in the car.â€</p>\n<p>There was the smile again, but this time I held out against it.</p>\n<p>â€œI donâ€™t like mysteries,â€ I answered, â€œand I donâ€™t understand why you</p>",
