        "<p>Tom laughed and turned to me.</p>\n<p>â€œDid you notice Daisyâ€™s face when that girl asked her to put her under</p>\n<p>a cold shower?â€</p>\n<p>Daisy began to sing with the music in a husky, rhythmic whisper,</p>\n<p>bringing out a meaning in each word that it had never had before and</p>\n<p>would never have again. When the melody rose her voice broke up</p>\n<p>sweetly, following it, in a way contralto voices have, and each change</p>",
        "<p>tipped out a little of her warm human magic upon the air.</p>\n<p>â€œLots of people come who havenâ€™t been invited,â€ she said</p>\n<p>suddenly. â€œThat girl hadnâ€™t been invited. They simply force their way</p>\n<p>in and heâ€™s too polite to object.â€</p>\n<p>â€œIâ€™d like to know who he is and what he does,â€ insisted Tom. â€œAnd I</p>\n<p>think Iâ€™ll make a point of finding out.â€</p>\n<p>â€œI can tell you right now,â€ she answered. â€œHe owned some drugstores, a</p>",
        "<p>lot of drugstores. He built them up himself.â€</p>\n<p>The dilatory limousine came rolling up the drive.</p>\n<p>â€œGood night, Nick,â€ said Daisy.</p>\n<p>Her glance left me and sought the lighted top of the steps, where</p>\n<p>â€œThree Oâ€™Clock in the Morning,â€ a neat, sad little waltz of that year,</p>\n<p>was drifting out the open door. After all, in the very casualness of</p>\n<p>Gatsbyâ€™s party there were romantic possibilities totally absent from</p>",
        "<p>her world. What was it up there in the song that seemed to be calling</p>\n<p>her back inside? What would happen now in the dim, incalculable hours?</p>\n<p>Perhaps some unbelievable guest would arrive, a person infinitely rare</p>\n<p>and to be marvelled at, some authentically radiant young girl who with</p>\n<p>one fresh glance at Gatsby, one moment of magical encounter, would</p>\n<p>blot out those five years of unwavering devotion.</p>\n<p>I stayed late that night. Gatsby asked me to wait until he was free,</p>",
        "<p>and I lingered in the garden until the inevitable swimming party had</p>\n<p>run up, chilled and exalted, from the black beach, until the lights</p>\n<p>were extinguished in the guestrooms overhead. When he came down the</p>\n<p>steps at last the tanned skin was drawn unusually tight on his face,</p>\n<p>and his eyes were bright and tired.</p>\n<p>â€œShe didnâ€™t like it,â€ he said immediately.</p>\n<p>â€œOf course she did.â€</p>",
        "<p>â€œShe didnâ€™t like it,â€ he insisted. â€œShe didnâ€™t have a good time.â€</p>\n<p>He was silent, and I guessed at his unutterable depression.</p>\n<p>â€œI feel far away from her,â€ he said. â€œItâ€™s hard to make her</p>\n<p>understand.â€</p>\n<p>â€œYou mean about the dance?â€</p>\n<p>â€œThe dance?â€ He dismissed all the dances he had given with a snap of</p>\n<p>his fingers. â€œOld sport, the dance is unimportant.â€</p>",
        "<p>He wanted nothing less of Daisy than that she should go to Tom and</p>\n<p>say: â€œI never loved you.â€ After she had obliterated four years with</p>\n<p>that sentence they could decide upon the more practical measures to be</p>\n<p>taken. One of them was that, after she was free, they were to go back</p>\n<p>to Louisville and be married from her houseâ€”just as if it were five</p>\n<p>years ago.</p>\n<p>â€œAnd she doesnâ€™t understand,â€ he said. â€œShe used to be able to</p>",
        "<p>understand. Weâ€™d sit for hoursâ€”â€</p>\n<p>He broke off and began to walk up and down a desolate path of fruit</p>\n<p>rinds and discarded favours and crushed flowers.</p>\n<p>â€œI wouldnâ€™t ask too much of her,â€ I ventured. â€œYou canâ€™t repeat the</p>\n<p>past.â€</p>\n<p>â€œCanâ€™t repeat the past?â€ he cried incredulously. â€œWhy of course you</p>\n<p>can!â€</p>",
        "<p>He looked around him wildly, as if the past were lurking here in the</p>\n<p>shadow of his house, just out of reach of his hand.</p>\n<p>â€œIâ€™m going to fix everything just the way it was before,â€ he said,</p>\n<p>nodding determinedly. â€œSheâ€™ll see.â€</p>\n<p>He talked a lot about the past, and I gathered that he wanted to</p>\n<p>recover something, some idea of himself perhaps, that had gone into</p>\n<p>loving Daisy. His life had been confused and disordered since then,</p>",
        "<p>but if he could once return to a certain starting place and go over it</p>\n<p>all slowly, he could find out what that thing was â€¦</p>\n<p>â€¦ One autumn night, five years before, they had been walking down the</p>\n<p>street when the leaves were falling, and they came to a place where</p>\n<p>there were no trees and the sidewalk was white with moonlight. They</p>\n<p>stopped here and turned toward each other. Now it was a cool night</p>\n<p>with that mysterious excitement in it which comes at the two changes</p>",
