        "<p>Gatsby took up his drink.</p>\n<p>â€œThey certainly look cool,â€ he said, with visible tension.</p>\n<p>We drank in long, greedy swallows.</p>\n<p>â€œI read somewhere that the sunâ€™s getting hotter every year,â€ said Tom</p>\n<p>genially. â€œIt seems that pretty soon the earthâ€™s going to fall into</p>\n<p>the sunâ€”or wait a minuteâ€”itâ€™s just the oppositeâ€”the sunâ€™s getting</p>\n<p>colder every year.</p>",
        "<p>â€œCome outside,â€ he suggested to Gatsby, â€œIâ€™d like you to have a look</p>\n<p>at the place.â€</p>\n<p>I went with them out to the veranda. On the green Sound, stagnant in</p>\n<p>the heat, one small sail crawled slowly toward the fresher sea.</p>\n<p>Gatsbyâ€™s eyes followed it momentarily; he raised his hand and pointed</p>\n<p>across the bay.</p>\n<p>â€œIâ€™m right across from you.â€</p>",
        "<p>â€œSo you are.â€</p>\n<p>Our eyes lifted over the rose-beds and the hot lawn and the weedy</p>\n<p>refuse of the dog-days alongshore. Slowly the white wings of the boat</p>\n<p>moved against the blue cool limit of the sky. Ahead lay the scalloped</p>\n<p>ocean and the abounding blessed isles.</p>\n<p>â€œThereâ€™s sport for you,â€ said Tom, nodding. â€œIâ€™d like to be out there</p>\n<p>with him for about an hour.â€</p>",
        "<p>We had luncheon in the dining-room, darkened too against the heat, and</p>\n<p>drank down nervous gaiety with the cold ale.</p>\n<p>â€œWhatâ€™ll we do with ourselves this afternoon?â€ cried Daisy, â€œand the</p>\n<p>day after that, and the next thirty years?â€</p>\n<p>â€œDonâ€™t be morbid,â€ Jordan said. â€œLife starts all over again when it</p>\n<p>gets crisp in the fall.â€</p>\n<p>â€œBut itâ€™s so hot,â€ insisted Daisy, on the verge of tears, â€œand</p>",
        "<p>everythingâ€™s so confused. Letâ€™s all go to town!â€</p>\n<p>Her voice struggled on through the heat, beating against it, moulding</p>\n<p>its senselessness into forms.</p>\n<p>â€œIâ€™ve heard of making a garage out of a stable,â€ Tom was saying to</p>\n<p>Gatsby, â€œbut Iâ€™m the first man who ever made a stable out of a</p>\n<p>garage.â€</p>\n<p>â€œWho wants to go to town?â€ demanded Daisy insistently. Gatsbyâ€™s eyes</p>",
        "<p>floated toward her. â€œAh,â€ she cried, â€œyou look so cool.â€</p>\n<p>Their eyes met, and they stared together at each other, alone in</p>\n<p>space. With an effort she glanced down at the table.</p>\n<p>â€œYou always look so cool,â€ she repeated.</p>\n<p>She had told him that she loved him, and Tom Buchanan saw. He was</p>\n<p>astounded. His mouth opened a little, and he looked at Gatsby, and</p>\n<p>then back at Daisy as if he had just recognized her as someone he knew</p>",
